{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":692,"record_hash":"sha256:075392067931b0048d0149030d8e7c8aecf2d1a519d392815fa952efefabeb2a","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:48:05.781Z","kind":"tool_call","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:custom_tool_call","role":null,"text":null,"tool_name":"apply_patch","tool_input":"*** Begin Patch\n*** Update File: agent-trail.md\n@@\n Given the current repository, the safer default is: Forge owns the website and\n JSON API contract; a separate generator service owns local repositories,\n GitMeta materialization, `but-agentlog`, and NAPI/Rust runtime concerns. Revisit\n putting the generator in Forge only after the actual deployment environment is\n confirmed to satisfy the runtime checklist above.\n+\n+## Online Research Findings (2026-05-24)\n+\n+Research was split across three lanes: Pierre/code.storage, deployment/runtime\n+fit, and Rust-to-Node integration.\n+\n+### Pierre / code.storage\n+\n+code.storage can help as a Git remote/cache, not as a mounted filesystem.\n+\n+Relevant findings:\n+\n+- code.storage Git Sync can mirror public GitHub repositories without GitHub App\n+  credentials through public mode, then refresh with `pullUpstream()`\n+  ([Public GitHub Sync](https://code.[REDACTED:entropy]),\n+  [Git Sync docs](https://code.storage/docs/guides/integrations)).\n+- code.storage also supports generic HTTPS Git sync for GitLab, Bitbucket,\n+  Gitea, Forgejo, Codeberg, SourceHut, and similar hosts\n+  ([Generic HTTPS Git sync](https://code.storage/changelog/generic-https-git-sync)).\n+- code.storage exposes normal Git operations over HTTPS: `git clone`,\n+  `git fetch`, `git pull`, and `git push` against JWT-authenticated remotes\n+  ([Git Operations](https://code.storage/docs/guides/git-operations)).\n+- The docs prove Git remote behavior, but do not prove that Git Sync mirrors\n+  arbitrary custom refs such as `refs/meta/main`. That needs a direct spike with\n+  `git ls-remote <code-storage-remote> 'refs/meta/*'`.\n+- No code.storage docs found indicate FUSE, mounted repo directories, or any\n+  mechanism that makes a remote repository appear as a local path to a server\n+  process.\n+\n+Implication: Pierre/code.storage is a good optional upstream for a generator\n+service's local scratch repository. It is not the generator runtime.\n+\n+### Deployment Runtime\n+\n+Vercel-style Next.js functions are a poor fit for Agent Trail generation.\n+\n+Relevant findings:\n+\n+- Vercel Functions have a read-only filesystem plus writable `/tmp` scratch\n+  space capped at 500 MB\n+  ([Vercel runtimes](https://vercel.com/docs/functions/runtimes)).\n+- Vercel Node functions have bounded duration, bundle size, memory, and file\n+  descriptor limits\n+  ([Vercel limits](https://vercel.com/docs/functions/limitations)).\n+- Vercel recommends object storage for persisted writes from functions\n+  ([Vercel files guide](https://vercel.[REDACTED:entropy])).\n+- Next can run native/server-only packages, but server dependencies are bundled\n+  by default; packages using Node-specific behavior may need\n+  `serverExternalPackages`\n+  ([Next serverExternalPackages](https://nextjs.[REDACTED:entropy])).\n+- Edge runtime is off the table for generation because it does not support the\n+  needed Node APIs\n+  ([Next Edge Runtime](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/edge)).\n+- Vercel Sandbox is interesting for experiments: it provides isolated Linux\n+  sandboxes with `git`, writable `/vercel/sandbox`, sudo, and beta automatic\n+  persistence\n+  ([Sandbox overview](https://vercel.com/docs/sandbox),\n+  [System specifications](https://vercel.[REDACTED:entropy]),\n+  [persistent sandbox beta](https://vercel.[REDACTED:entropy])).\n+  It is still a sandbox product, not the default production home for a durable\n+  Git cache.\n+\n+Better deployment shape: a container/VM worker with a mounted volume.\n+\n+- Fly.io volumes are local persistent storage for Fly Machines\n+  ([Fly volumes](https://fly.io/docs/volumes/overview/)).\n+- Render paid web services, private services, and background workers can attach\n+  persistent disks; default service filesystems are ephemeral\n+  ([Render disks](https://render.com/docs/disks)).\n+- Railway volumes mount read/write persistent storage into a service\n+  ([Railway volumes](https://docs.railway.com/volumes)).\n+\n+Implication: if Forge is deployed like Vercel/serverless, generation should move\n+out. If Forge is deployed as a long-lived container with a persistent volume,\n+in-process generation remains possible but still needs explicit cache and\n+locking design.\n+\n+### Rust / Node Boundary\n+\n+NAPI is the cleanest Rust-to-Node bridge only if generation runs inside Forge's\n+Node process. A separate generator service can avoid the bridge entirely.\n+\n+Relevant findings:\n+\n+- Node-API is ABI-stable across Node versions, which makes it the right native\n+  addon foundation\n+  ([Node-API docs](https://nodejs.org/api/n-api.html)).\n+- `napi-rs` can build Rust native addons and emit platform-suffixed `.node`\n+  artifacts such as `index.darwin-x64.node`\n+  ([napi-rs CLI](https://napi-rs.github.io/napi-rs/cli/)).\n+- A helper binary is operationally simpler than NAPI in some deployments because\n+  it isolates crashes and avoids native addon bundling, but it still requires\n+  binary packaging, filesystem access, `git`, and a cache.\n+- WASM/WASI is a bad fit. Node's WASI support is still marked experimental, and\n+  Rust's base WASI target does not support process spawning. Agent Trail wants\n+  real Git repository behavior, so WASM adds friction without removing the hard\n+  dependency.\n+\n+Implication: if the generator is separate, prefer a small Rust HTTP worker that\n+links the projection API directly. If the generator must run in Forge, prefer a\n+dedicated `but-agenttrail-napi` package and externalize it from Next bundling.\n+\n+### Current Recommendation\n+\n+Build this as two deployable pieces:\n+\n+- Forge: URL replacement, GitHub PR lookup, public JSON contract, status polling,\n+  snapshot route, and UI.\n+- Agent Trail generator service: local repository cache, metadata fetch,\n+  GitMeta materialization, `but-agentlog` projection, locking, cleanup, and\n+  result storage.\n+\n+The generator service can still live near GitButler code at first, because the\n+main API work is in `but-agentlog`. It should not be fused into Forge unless the\n+Forge deployment runtime is confirmed to match the stateful-worker checklist.\n+\n+Required spikes before committing to Pierre/code.storage in the hot path:\n+\n+1. create or sync a public repository with `refs/meta/main` into code.storage\n+2. run `git ls-remote <code-storage-remote> 'refs/meta/*'`\n+3. fetch that ref into a local scratch repository and run a minimal\n+   `git-meta-lib` materialization\n+4. measure first-run and warm-run timings for public GitHub remote vs\n+   code.storage remote\n \n Example local setup:\n*** End Patch\n","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:48:05.781Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"custom_tool_call","status":"completed","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]","name":"apply_patch"}}}